<subSubSection lastPageId="9" pageId="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,485,1551,1611]" box="[151,266,1586,1611]" pageId="8">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,258,1586,1611]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 5" captionStart-1="FIGURE 6" captionStartId-0="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionStartId-1="10.[151,250,1375,1397]" captionTargetBox-0="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetBox-1="[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetId-0="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId-1="figure@10.[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetPageId-0="9" captionTargetPageId-1="10" captionText-0="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." captionText-1="FIGURE 6. Ptygura libera, scanning electron microscope photographs of trophi. A. Complete set, frontal view. B. Complete set, caudal view. C. Unci and rami, frontal view. D. Unci and rami, caudal view. Scale bar: A–D: 2 µm." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/2673295/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Figs 5–6</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1658,2007]" pageId="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,441,1658,1683]" pageId="8">Redescription of female.</emphasis>
Corona (
<figureCitation box="[546,679,1658,1683]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5A, 5E</figureCitation>
) large, bilobate (circular corona with a dorsal gap in 
<bibRefCitation author="Myers, F. J." box="[1276,1431,1658,1683]" pageId="8" pagination="231 - 233" refId="ref5204" refString="Myers, F. J. (1934) A new species of Rotatoria (Ptygura libera). (With observations on Euchlanis pellucidula Harring and Euchlanis triquetra Ehrenberg). Journal of the Royal Microscopical Society, 54, 231 - 233." type="journal article" year="1934">Myers (1934)</bibRefCitation>
, misinterpreted trilobate in 
<bibRefCitation author="Nogrady, T." box="[465,659,1694,1719]" pageId="8" pagination="425 - 436" refId="ref5249" refString="Nogrady, T. (1976) Canadian rotifers. I. Lac Echo, Quebec. Le Naturaliste Canadien, 103, 425 - 436." type="journal article" year="1976">Nogrady (1976))</bibRefCitation>
with a dorsal indentation and two red apical eyespots. Corona a circumapical band, well developed dorsally, poorly developed latero-ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1041,1127,1730,1755]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
), interrupted ventrally. One frontal protuberance in contracted stage (
<figureCitation box="[608,695,1766,1791]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). Neck indistinct, and body smoothly tapering into retractable foot of medium length, which terminates in a long peduncle anchoring to a membranous structure (
<figureCitation box="[1286,1428,1802,1827]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5A, 5F</figureCitation>
) connecting to the tube. Head and anterior part of the trunk usually bent dorsally while swimming (
<figureCitation box="[1268,1356,1838,1863]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
). Anus near middle of the trunk, opening upwardly on the dorsal side (
<figureCitation box="[881,1022,1874,1899]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5C, 5D</figureCitation>
). Lateral antennae long and slender. Tube (
<figureCitation box="[222,338,1910,1935]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 5A, F</figureCitation>
) transparent oval to pyriform, inner sheath conspicuous, distinct cylindrical, outer layer gelatinous and difficult to see. Usually one or two eggs next to the foot.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1658,2007]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1437,151,789]" lastPageId="9" pageId="8">
Trophi malleoramate (
<figureCitation box="[461,535,1982,2007]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1375,1397]" captionTargetBox="[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Ptygura libera, scanning electron microscope photographs of trophi. A. Complete set, frontal view. B. Complete set, caudal view. C. Unci and rami, frontal view. D. Unci and rami, caudal view. Scale bar: A–D: 2 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673295/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), nearly symmetrical. Unci plates consist of right/left: 14–15/14–15 weakly webbed teeth. Three right and four left major teeth almost straight with long lanceolate head. Minor teeth head sharply pointed. Rami elongate-triangular with short blunt alulae. Median rami apophyses inapparent in caudal view. Basal apophyses moderately developed. Manubria crescent-shaped with three chambers. Fulcrum short, with a weakly developed basal plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
